text.b: Santa Cruz Shakespeare, Santa Cruz, California

page.text: Hatch Mott MacDonald (HMM) has provided traffic engineering services for the
proposed Santa Cruz Shakespeare performance festival theater site in Santa Cruz,
Currently, performances for Santa Cruz Shakespeare are being held at the
Sinsheimer-Stanley Festival Glen, an outdoor performing arts venue at the University
of California at Santa Cruz (UCSC). However, UCSC has chosen not to renew the
lease permitting use of its property for future performances. Santa Cruz Shakespeare
is proposing to construct a new outdoor theater venue for its performances within
Delaveaga Park, adjacent to the former Stroke Center. This study evaluates the
potential traffic impacts of relocating the performances to the Delaveaga Park
Exhibit 1 depicts the study area, while Exhibit 2 depicts the study layout plan within
This analysis evaluates traffic conditions during a typical performance schedule for
Santa Cruz Shakespeare. Note that performances are only held during the summer
months, and do not reflect anticipated conditions during other times of the year. The
potential project impacts would occur only during the performance season and are
not impacts that would occur year-round.

The following significance criteria were used to determine if the project would
represent a significant impact on the study intersections and roadway segments:
• If the level of service (LOS) without project traffic on an intersection or a
roadway segment operates at an acceptable level of service (LOS) within the
City of Santa Cruz – i.e. LOS A, B, C or D – but, after the project traffic is
added, degrades to an unacceptable level of service – i.e. LOS E or F – the
project would represent a significant impact on that intersection or roadway
• If the LOS without project traffic on an intersection or a roadway segment
operates at an deficient level of service (LOS) within the City of Santa Cruz
– i.e. LOS E or F – and, after the project traffic is added, remains at an
unacceptable level of service – i.e. LOS E or F – and the project traffic would
increase the traffic volumes at that intersection or segment by at least 3.0%,
the project would represent a significant impact on that intersection or

Santa Cruz Shakespeare conducts 30-40 performances per year, all within the three
summer months (i.e. June, July, and August), with the bulk of those performances in
July and August. During weekdays (Tuesday through Friday), performances
typically begin at 8:00 PM, while 2:00 PM and 8:00 PM performances are staged on
Saturdays and Sundays. Performance lengths can vary, depending upon the play
being performed, but are typically about 2 hours and 15 minutes in length.
Performances for Santa Cruz Shakespeare currently attract 300–350 people per
performance, but a single performance can attract as many as 500 people. The
proposed outdoor theater will have seating for a maximum of 482 people.

This analysis assumes that there will be one weekday performance (at 8:00 PM)
and two weekend performances (at 2:00 PM and 8:00 PM) on any given day in
the summer, with each performance attracting a maximum capacity of 500
people. This number of performances and attendance constitute a conservative
basis for the potential impacts of the proposed project.
Attendees at Santa Cruz Shakespeare performance can arrive as early as two
hours prior the start of a performance. However, dispersal after a performance
begins 5-10 minutes after a performance and lasts for about an hour, with most
attendees leaving within 10 minutes of returning to the parking area. More
information about arrival to and dispersal rates from a performance can be found
Exhibit 5 summarizes the project trip generation, and is repeated from the
aforementioned trip generation memorandum. The project is estimated to
generate 540 weekday daily trips, with 5 trips (5 in, 0 out) during the Weekday
PM peak hour, and 1,040 weekend daily trips, with 128 trips (128 in, 0 out)
during the Saturday Mid-Afternoon peak hour. Note that these trips would only
be generated on days with a performance, which occurs only during three months
out of the entire year (specifically June, July, and August), not year-round.

Exhibit 10 summarizes the projected parking demand for the project. Parking
demand was quantified via the following three different methods:
1. Parking occupancy counts during two Santa Cruz Shakespeare performances;
2. The current City of Santa Cruz Municipal Code parking requirements;
3. Parking generation rates from Parking Generation, 4
the Institute of Transportation Engineers in 2010;
Existing parking occupancy was counted on August 16, 2015 at both the 2:00 PM
and 8:00 PM performances. The parking occupancy (or number of parked cars) at
each performance was counted twice – approximately 15 minutes after the start of the
performance and 30 minutes prior to the end of the performance – to obtain the
maximum number of vehicles attending each performance. The parking occupancies
for each performance were averaged together and then linearly extrapolated (from the
average attendance of 326 people at the two surveyed performances) to project the
parking occupancy for a full performance event at the study project site
The parking requirements per the City of Santa Cruz Municipal Code were quantified
using the “Theater” land use (Municipal Code Section 24.12.240).
Finally, parking requirements were also quantified using the “Live Theater” land use
Edition, published by the Institute of
As shown in Exhibit 10, the largest parking demand was projected via the parking
occupancy counts, which project that the maximum parking demand at a performance
at the project site would be 233 cars.
The exact parking areas that will be used to accommodate the parking demand during
a performance have not yet been identified, but presumably may include the former
Stroke Center parking area adjacent to the site and/or the parking area surrounding
the Delaveaga Lodge Restaurant. Use of the latter parking area should be
coordinated with the city Parks and Recreation Department and the Delaveaga Lodge
Restaurant, so as not to simultaneously schedule use of the parking area for
performances and also major events at the golf course or the restaurant. If multiple
parking areas are needed to accommodate parking during performances, parking staff
are also recommended to direct attendees to the correct parking areas (including
directing attendees away from parking lots that are full or nearly full).
The Santa Cruz County Emergency Operations Center is located immediately north
of the project site. While most of its parking lot is gated, there are about 20 spaces
that are open to the public. The potential use of those spaces by attendees of
performances would need to be negotiated with Santa Cruz County.
In summary, the project would generate an estimated 540 weekday daily trips
(including 5 trips during the Weekday PM peak hour) and 1,040 weekend daily trips
(including 128 trips during the Saturday Mid-Afternoon peak hour). These trips
would only be generated on days with a performance, which occurs only during three
months out of the entire year (specifically June, July, and August), not year-round.
The project would not represent a significant impact on the street network.
The maximum parking demand for the project would be 233 vehicles. Use of the
parking area surrounding the Delaveaga Lodge Restaurant should be coordinated
with the city Parks and Recreation Department and the Delaveaga Lodge Restaurant.
